article.description:
UCLA defeated Arizona State 66-58 Thursday night for the
Bruins' first 5-0 Pac-10 start in nine years.
article.headline: UCLA edges Stanford for top rank in Pac-10
article.linkText: UCLA rips Arizona St, now 5-0 in Pac-10
article.story: LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UCLA doubled, tripled and sometimes quadrupled Arizona State center Ike Diogu. Shutting down the Pac-10's best player earned the Bruins sole possession of first place in the conference. T.J. Cummings had 21 points, 12 rebounds and provided one of the big bodies on Diogu in UCLA's 66-58 victory Thursday night. It's the Bruins' first 5-0 Pac-10 start in nine years. "The emphasis for me is just to be relentless and never take a possession off," Cummings said. "I saw open shots and just took them when they came to me. I'm so proud of our guys. We're not letting ourselves get rattled." UCLA (9-3) is alone in first place, ahead of idle Stanford (4-0). The Bruins were a season removed from winning the 1995 national championship when they opened conference play with a 5-0 mark under Jim Harrick. "This team is good," Sun Devils coach Rob Evans said of the Bruins. "This cat (coach Ben Howland) has been around a while winning. Ben is doing a good job, the team plays well and the big difference is experience." Arizona State (6-7, 0-4) lost its fifth straight game and had its three-game winning streak against the Bruins snapped. Last season, the Sun Devils swept UCLA for just the second time in school history. "This is the worst feeling in the world," said Jason Braxton, who added 13 points. Diogu fouled out for just the fourth time in his career with 4:29 remaining and finished with 15 points -- below his Pac-10-leading average of 23.4. The sophomore extended his streak of double-figure scoring games to 45, which leads the nation. "I can't go out and shoot 100 percent every night. Tonight was just an off-night for me, I guess," Diogu said. "When I got the ball I made quick moves to the basket trying to avoid the double team. I was missing open shots that I normally make." Diogu grabbed six rebounds -- three less than his average -- as the Sun Devils were outrebounded 39-29. "This is the biggest team we will face all year. We have to do a better job on the boards," said Steve Moore, who led the Sun Devils with 17 points. Arizona State shot just 35 percent for the game. The Bruins have had trouble holding onto leads recently, and they nearly let another one get away. Dijon Thompson hit a 3-pointer to give UCLA a 54-42 lead. Then Diogu scored his last basket and Braxton took over, scoring 11 straight points to draw the Sun Devils to 59-55 with 42 seconds left. Cummings hit two free throws for a 61-55 lead. Then Wilfried Fameni hit a 3-pointer to get Arizona State within three points with 24 seconds left. Thompson kept up his recent clutch performances at the line, hitting two free throws for a 65-58 lead. "It's a composure thing," Cummings said. "They hit us with a couple shots and we didn't let it devastate us." Thompson added 19 points and Trevor Ariza had 16 for UCLA, which made 12-of-14 free throws over the final 4{ minutes. "Our free-throw shooting in the second half was great. The practice is paying off," Howland said.
